        content: "The present invention provides a predictive perimenopause detection system that identifies the onset of perimenopause through continuous analysis of wearable physiological data using a multi-signal convergence scoring architecture. The system employs six weighted signal categories: follicular phase basal body temperature elevation weighted at thirty percent, menstrual cycle length variability weighted at twenty percent, heart rate variability trajectory weighted at fifteen percent, sleep architecture changes weighted at fifteen percent, thermoregulatory event detection weighted at ten percent, and self-reported indicators weighted at ten percent.\n\nThe primary novel insight of this invention is the identification of follicular phase basal body temperature elevation as a predictive biomarker for perimenopause onset. As estrogen levels begin to decline in early perimenopause, the temperature-suppressing effect of estrogen on the hypothalamic thermoregulatory center diminishes, resulting in measurable elevation of follicular phase temperatures. This elevation precedes the cycle irregularity and symptom onset that define clinical perimenopause detection. By monitoring continuous temperature data from a wearable device and comparing against the user's personal follicular phase temperature baseline, the system can detect this elevation years before conventional clinical diagnosis.\n\nThe system generates a Transition Likelihood Level on a five-point scale from zero through four, with each level corresponding to specific confidence thresholds and triggering appropriate clinical recommendations. At level three and above, the system recommends confirmatory laboratory testing including day three hormone panel measurements of follicle-stimulating hormone, luteinizing hormone, estradiol, anti-Mullerian hormone, and thyroid-stimulating hormone, with results feeding back into the prediction model to dramatically increase detection confidence.\n\nFor users with one or more years of menstrual cycle monitoring data from prior system use, detection sensitivity is significantly enhanced because the system compares against the individual's established personal baseline rather than population averages. A follicular phase temperature rise of zero point three degrees Fahrenheit from a user's established personal average is clinically significant even when the absolute temperature remains below the population-level threshold."
