        content: "1. A computer-implemented method for coordinated multi-partner reproductive health optimization comprising: maintaining a first health profile for a first partner and a second health profile for a second partner, each profile storing physiological data, health scores, intervention records, and supplement compliance data independently; ingesting data for the first partner from at least one continuous wearable monitoring device providing cycle-related physiological signals including basal body temperature, heart rate variability, and sleep architecture; ingesting data for the second partner from at least periodic semen analysis results and daily lifestyle factor tracking inputs; computing a shared reproductive outcome model that estimates joint conception probability as a function of both partners' current physiological states, said model incorporating compensatory interactions wherein strength in one partner's contribution partially compensates for weakness in the other, complementary interactions wherein both partners' contributions must exceed minimum thresholds, and timing interactions wherein temporal alignment of both partners' optimal states affects joint probability; and generating coordinated intervention plans for both partners through a joint optimization algorithm that recalculates both partners' protocol priorities whenever new data arrives from either partner, said algorithm identifying the current binding constraint across both partners and distributing intervention intensity to maximize marginal improvement in joint conception probability.\n\n2. The method of claim 1, wherein the joint optimization algorithm performs dynamic rebalancing comprising: detecting a significant change in one partner's health data; recalculating the shared reproductive outcome model to identify whether the binding constraint has shifted between partners; if the binding constraint has shifted, generating updated protocol priorities for both partners reflecting the new constraint; and delivering coordinated communications to both partners explaining the protocol adjustment in terms of joint progress, wherein a change in one partner's data may result in protocol priority changes for the other partner.\n\n3. The method of claim 1, further comprising a privacy-preserving data sharing layer implementing configurable visibility tiers between partners comprising: a full transparency tier enabling both partners to view all health data for both profiles; a summary sharing tier enabling partners to view aggregate scores and trends without individual clinical values; an action-only sharing tier limiting visibility to joint action items and timing recommendations; and an independent mode with no inter-partner data sharing; wherein each partner independently selects their visibility tier and the effective visibility is determined by the more restrictive selection of the two partners.\n\n4. The method of claim 1, further comprising timeline coordination comprising: computing a spermatogenesis-adjusted intervention schedule for the second partner's protocols accounting for approximately seventy-two day sperm development cycles; computing cycle-phase-aligned intervention timing for the first partner's protocols; identifying target fertile windows where both partners' interventions are projected to reach peak effectiveness simultaneously; and generating a coordinated timeline visualization showing intervention onset, expected effect windows, and optimal conception attempt timing for the couple.\n\n5. The method of claim 1, wherein the coordinated intervention plans are generated subject to an adherence capacity constraint comprising: estimating each partner's remaining capacity for behavioral change based on current protocol burden and historical adherence patterns; evaluating whether adding a highest-priority intervention to one partner would exceed their estimated adherence capacity; and if capacity would be exceeded, substituting a lower-priority intervention for the other partner that produces comparable joint probability improvement while remaining within both partners' capacity bounds, thereby distributing intervention intensity across the couple to maximize total adherence-weighted impact.\n\n6. A coordinated reproductive health optimization system comprising: a dual-profile data store maintaining independent health profiles for two partners linked through a shared reproductive outcome identifier; a first data ingestion pipeline configured to process continuous wearable physiological data from a first partner including basal body temperature, heart rate variability, sleep architecture, and glucose monitoring data; a second data ingestion pipeline configured to process periodic semen analysis results and daily lifestyle factor inputs from a second partner; a shared reproductive outcome model configured to compute joint conception probability incorporating compensatory, complementary, and timing interaction effects between both partners' physiological contributions; a joint optimization algorithm configured to recalculate both partners' intervention priorities upon receipt of new data from either partner, subject to adherence capacity constraints and biological timeline alignment; a privacy-preserving data sharing layer implementing configurable multi-tier visibility between partners; and a coordinated AI care team comprising multiple specialized agents operating with awareness of both partners' health contexts and delivering recommendations through individual partner interfaces with privacy-compliant framing."
