        title: "CLAIMS",
        content: "1. A computer-implemented method for automated lifecycle health management comprising: continuously monitoring physiological data from at least one wearable device worn by a user across a plurality of reproductive lifecycle phases; automatically detecting physiological state transitions from the monitored data using phase-specific detection criteria, said transitions comprising at least fertility optimization to pregnancy detected from sustained basal body temperature elevation beyond normal luteal phase duration, pregnancy to postpartum detected from delivery-associated physiological changes, and menstrual monitoring to perimenopause detected from multi-signal convergence scoring; upon detecting each transition, automatically reconfiguring the health management platform across five dimensions comprising scoring algorithm parameters, monitoring protocols, care team behavior, intervention strategies, and content delivery, to match the requirements of the new lifecycle phase; and maintaining complete longitudinal data continuity across all transitions, wherein all physiological data, scoring history, intervention records, and care team interactions from prior phases are preserved and available to inform monitoring and care in subsequent phases.\n\n2. The method of claim 1, wherein detecting the fertility-to-pregnancy transition comprises identifying sustained basal body temperature elevation beyond cycle day sixteen without decline toward follicular baseline, concurrent heart rate variability changes associated with early pregnancy, and absence of pre-menstrual temperature decline, enabling probable conception detection before a missed period.\n\n3. The method of claim 1, wherein the data continuity layer provides cross-phase baseline enrichment wherein each successive lifecycle phase establishes personalized monitoring thresholds based on accumulated physiological baselines from all prior phases, and intervention response persistence wherein intervention effectiveness demonstrated in prior phases informs intervention selection in subsequent phases.\n\n4. The method of claim 1, further comprising detecting transitions from menstrual monitoring to condition-specific management for polycystic ovary syndrome and endometriosis based on pattern analysis of cycle length, ovulation indicators, and symptom clusters, and reconfiguring monitoring to condition-aware mode with enhanced relevant signal monitoring and clinical referral recommendations.\n\n5. The method of claim 1, wherein care team behavior adaptation comprises adjusting the prominence, communication style, and clinical focus of a plurality of specialized AI care agents based on lifecycle phase, including activating phase-specific specialist agents and adjusting agent communication style based on user age and phase context while maintaining consistent agent personality.\n\n6. A lifecycle health management system comprising: a transition detection engine configured to continuously evaluate wearable data and self-reported inputs against phase-specific transition criteria for a plurality of reproductive lifecycle transitions; a platform reconfiguration module configured to simultaneously update scoring algorithms, monitoring protocols, care team behavior, intervention strategies, and content delivery upon transition detection; a data continuity layer configured to maintain a unified longitudinal health record spanning all lifecycle phases with complete signal retention, cross-phase baseline enrichment, and intervention response persistence; and a transition confirmation module configured to validate physiologically-detected transitions through user confirmation or laboratory testing before initiating irreversible platform reconfiguration.\n\n7. The system of claim 6, wherein the transition detection engine supports at least eight lifecycle transitions comprising menarche preparation to menstrual establishment, menstrual monitoring to condition-specific management, menstrual monitoring to fertility optimization, fertility optimization to pregnancy, pregnancy to postpartum recovery, postpartum recovery to menstrual monitoring or fertility optimization, menstrual monitoring to perimenopause, and perimenopause to post-menopause."
